{"questionId":"19760","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The weights of apples on a tree can be modelled by a normal distribution with a mean of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>85</mn></math> grams and a standard deviation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math> grams.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A sample of apples are taken from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> trees, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math>, in different parts of the orchard.</p>\n<p>The data is shown in the table below.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/b67346e4383d915fd6962466c3bcb578d10416ad.png\"></p>\n<p>The owner of the orchard wants to know whether the mean weight of the apples from tree&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>)</mo></math> is greater than the mean weight of the apples from tree <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>)</mo></math> so sets up the&nbsp;following test:</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mtext>H</mtext><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>:</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mtext>H</mtext><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>:</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></math></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi></math>-value for the owner’s test.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi></math>-value <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0189</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>018947</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>(M1)A1</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>[2 marks]</strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19760","referenceCode":"EXN.1.SL.TZ0.3b.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the p-value for the owner’s test.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.11—Expected, observed, hypotheses, chi squared, gof, t-test"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}